<TEXT>atha kālaṃ tithiṃ vāraṃ nakṣatraṃ yogam{ }uttamam |</TEXT>
<TEXT>nimittaṃ guṇaval{ }lagnaṃ sūryācandramasor{ }balam || 2:1||</TEXT>
<TEXT>labdhvā samyag{ }anugrāhyaṃ bhūtidīkṣāvidhau guruḥ |</TEXT>
<TEXT>śivaṃ sayajñadravyāṅgaṃ kṛtanityo'dhivāsayet || 2:2||</TEXT>
<TRANS>Then, having determined (\skt{labdhvā}) correctly (\skt{samyak}) the time, the lunar day, the weekday, the asterism, best yoga, [a good] omen, an excellent lagna, and a strong [position] of sun and moon, the guru, after completing the daily obligatory rituals (\skt{kṛtanityaḥ}), should incubate (\skt{adhivāsayet}) the person worthy of grace (\skt{anugrāhyam}), [who is to become a] Śiva, along with the wherewithal for worship,
for the performance of an initiation for special powers (\skt{bhūtidīkṣāvidhau}).</TRANS>
<PARAL>We are uncertain about \skt{śivam}.  We have taken it as proleptic and referring to the initiand, but it is possible that Śiva is present in some other form, a pot or liṅga, and must be also be incubated, along with the initiand and the equipment for worship.  Also possible is that \skt{śivam} may be a corruption of \skt{śiṣyaṃ}.</PARAL>
<TEXT>tatra kālo vinā varṣāḥ puṣyacaitrañ{ }ca śobhanaḥ |</TEXT>
<APP>\vb <LEM> puṣyacaitrañca </LEM> \msApc, paṣyacaitrañca \msAac </APP>
<TEXT>dīkṣāyām{ }abhiṣeke ca vratagrahaṇamokṣayoḥ || 2:3||</TEXT>
<TRANS>Among those [above-listed circumstances], an auspicious time for [the performance of] initiation, consecration [as a \skt{sādhaka} or guru], and for adopting or relinquishing a religious observance, would be without rains, [particularly] the months of Puṣya and Caitra.</TRANS>

<TEXT>tithayo ’kṣīṇavidhavo vārarkṣair{ }avidūṣitāḥ |</TEXT>
<TEXT>bhuktyai muktyai samopetā kṛṣṇāṣṭamyāṃ ca bhūtayā || 2:4||</TEXT>
% Perhaps error for: samopetāḥ kṛṣṇāṣṭamyā ca bhūtaye, “[the above days] together with the 8th day of the dark fortnight, for [initiation for the sake of] supernatural powers”.
<TRANS>The lunar days when the moon is not diminished, [as long as they are] not spoiled by [inappropriate] weekdays or asterisms, [are suitable] for supernatural powers [and] for liberation; [the above days] together with the 8th day of the dark fortnight, for [initiation for the sake of] supernatural powers.
</TRANS>
<TEXT>abhaumārkkigrahāṇāñ{ }ca vāraṃ kāmikasiddhidam |</TEXT>
<TEXT>aviṣṭigaralaṃ cāpi karaṇaṃ karaṇaṃ mudāṃ || 2:5||</TEXT>
%% \msA fol. 28b (=26v in Newari numeration)
<TRANS>A weekday of [any of] the planets that are not Tuesday or Saturday bestows all manner of desired success. A \skt{karaṇa} other than [the \skt{karaṇa}s called] \skt{viṣṭi} and \skt{garala} is a \skt{karaṇa} that produces joy.
</TRANS>
<TEXT>nakṣatrāṇi ca yāge'smin praśastāni caturdaśa |</TEXT>
<TEXT>brāhmyaṃ saumyaṃ prajeśānadaivataṃ gurudaivatam || 2:6||</TEXT>
<APP>\vc <LEM>prajeśāna° </LEM> \emend; prajesāna° \msA </APP>
<TRANS>The asterisms recommended for this [major] ritual are fourteen: Brāhmya, Saumya, Prajeśānadaivata, Gurudaivata, Paitrya, Bhāskaradaivatya, Pāvana, Maitradaivata, Nairṛta, Vaiṣṇava, Pauṣṇa, and the three Uttaras [namely: Uttara, Uttaraphālguna and Uttaraproṣṭhapada].
</TRANS>
<TEXT>paitryaṃ bhāskaradaivatyaṃ pāvanaṃ maitradaivataṃ |</TEXT>
<TEXT>nairṛtaṃ vaiṣṇavaṃ pauṣṇam uttarās{ }tisra eva hi || 2:7||</TEXT>
<APP>\vc <LEM> nairṛtaṃ </LEM> \emend ; nairitaṃ \msA </APP>
<TEXT>apraśastaiḥ praśastaiś{ }ca nāmabhir{ }darśitakriyāḥ |</TEXT>
<TEXT>navāṣṭādaśa yogāś{ }ca tyāgopādeyagocarāḥ || 2:8||</TEXT>
<TR>The twenty-seven yogas have the rituals [that are appropriated to them] shown by their names, which are auspicious [in some cases] and inauspicious [in others], [and which are accordingly] to be avoided or sought after.</TR>
<TEXT>cāturmāsyanimittāni vaiśākhyadamanotsavaḥ |</TEXT>
<APP>\va <LEM> cāturmāsya° </LEM> \conj; cāturmāsyā \msApc; caturmāsyā \msAac </APP>
<PARAL>/2.9ab qu. with attr. in Somasambhupaddhativyākhyā p. 132:
   ata eva brahmaśambhupādaiḥ pavitrotsave damanotsave’pi dīkṣā kāryety uktam:
   cāturmāsyanimittāni vaiśākhadamanotsave</PARAL>
<TEXT>ayane viṣuve rāhudarśanaṃ guruparvva ca || 2:9|| </TEXT>
<TR>The occasions [that are recommended for this (skt dīkṣā) rite] are [the special days uses for pavitrotsava that fall] in the four months [of the rainy season], [and] the Damanotsava, which falls in the month of Vaiśākha.  [Also] the turns [of the sun to the north and south], the equinoxes, eclipses (rāhudarśanam) and Guruparvan.</TR>
<PARAL>Should we emend cāturmāsyā to cāturmāsye or  cāturmāsya° ?</PARAL>
<TEXT>loke vede prasiddhāś{ }ca tithayo devatodbhavāḥ |</TEXT>
<APP>\vb <LEM> tithayo </LEM> \msApc; tiyo \msAac </APP>
<TEXT>nimittam iti tat{ }sarvvaṃ kīrttitaṃ śāstrapaṇḍitaiḥ || 2:10||</TEXT>
<TR>The [recommended] lunar days are those well known in worldly and Vedic contexts as being produced by [particular] deities.  All of the above are proclaimed to be special occasions (\skt{nimittam}) by those well-versed in scriptures.
</TR>
<PARAL>Each \skt{tithi} is associated with a particular deity: see, e.g., \auth{Einoo} 2005 and \auth{Kafle} 2020.</PARAL>
