<TEXT>anukūlārthasaṃvittiḥ pratikūlakṣayānugā || 2:12||</TEXT>
%% \msA fol 27a (=27v in Newari numeration)
%%Note that this follows from what has been mistakenly numbered 28 in the modern Arabic numeration !
<TR>One who has the characteristics that have been taught [already in some previous chapter ?] may receive initiation (\skt{anugrāhyaḥ}).  Power (\skt{bhūtiḥ}) has as its means of achievement such things as mantras (\skt{mantrādisādhanā}). It is commensurate with the wealth and knowledge [of the initiand] (\skt{anukūlārthasaṃvittiḥ}), ???? (\skt{pratikūlakṣayānugā})</TR>
<NOTE>This is a continuation of the discussion of the terms of art introduced in the opening of the chapter, in verses 1 and 2.</NOTE>
<TEXT>tatsādhakatamaṃ dīkṣā śivasya karaṇaṃ viduḥ |</TEXT>
<APP> \vb <LEM> viduḥ </LEM> \conj; vibhum \msA </APP>
<TEXT>vyaktisthānam idaṃ cāsya yad{ }rajomaṇḍalādikam || 2:13||</TEXT>
<TR>It is known (\skt{viduḥ}) that the most effective instrument of Śiva for producing that (\skt{tat°}) [\skt{bhūti}] is initiation. This [place], where there is a maṇḍala of powders and so forth, is the place for making manifest that [condition of being Śiva] (\skt{asya}).</TR>
<NOTE>This is an implicit allusion to Pāṇini's rule 1.4.42 \skt{sādhakatamaṃ karaṇam}.  Brahmaśambhu seems to be going through the \skt{kāraka}s, the causal factors, necessary for an initiation.</NOTE>
