<TEXT>agnau saṃtarpaṇaṃ ceti pūrvvamadhyāhnayor api || 2:17||</TEXT>
<TR>[As for the] daily obligatory actions [mentioned in 2:2] (\skt{nityam}), [they comprise:] calls of nature (\skt{āvaśyakam}), purificatory ablutions, bathing, [rites of] the junctures of the day, worship of Śiva, and satisfying [performed by libations] into the fire.  The above (\skt{iti}) [are to be performed] in the forenoon and afternoon.</TR>
<TEXT>tac{ }ca nityānusaṃdhāne pūrvvaṃ yena mayoditam|</TEXT>
<TEXT>teneha na punar{ }vācyaṃ naimittikakriyākrame || 2:18||</TEXT>
<TR>Because I have explained this [above-said group of activities] earlier in the “Synthesis of Regular Obligatory Acts” (\skt{nityānusandhāne}), so, therefore they do not need to be stated again in this serial account of ritual actions that are obligatory on particular occasions (\skt{naimittikakriyākrame}).</TR>
<NOTE>This confirms that the author has composed another work (or perhaps rather part of this work) called the \skt{Nityānusaṃdhāna}, fragments of which are transmitted in a manuscript in Nepal (NGMPP Reel No.\ C 48/2).</NOTE>
