<TR>White, red, black, yellowish (āpīta) and green powders; precious gems, minerals, seeds, flowers and honeys.
These, in accordance with one’s wealth, one should make ready, one by one (\skt{pṛthak pṛthak}), in due order, by means of [recitation over them of] the mantras of the [five] \skt{kalā}s beginning with Śāntyatītā.</TR>
<NOTE>There are two lists here of five things, the first being a list of powders of five colours.  We assume that each element of the two groups of five has a corresponding mantra in the set of five \skt{kalāmantra}s beginning with Śāntyatītā, and that mantra must be recited over that particular element.
We have taken \skt{dalaja} as honey since we can imagine no other sense for it.  As for the plural, one could take it to refer to varieties of honey, or one could assume that the plural is simply the result of the word being at the end of a \skt{dvandva} compound, and that what is plural is the flowers.</NOTE>
<TEXT>api naimittikāṃgāni saṃpādyaivam{ }anantaram |</TEXT>
<TEXT>paśvanugrahasāmarthyāt patyur{ }ātmani yojayet || 2:35||</TEXT>
<APP> \vc <LEM> @sāmarthyāt</LEM> \emend; @sāmarthyā \msA </APP>
<TR> Thus having gathered together (\skt{sampādya}) also (\skt{api}) the constituent elements for rites that are obligatory on particular occasions (\skt{naimittikāṃgāni}), after that (\skt{anantaram}), by the power of the Lord to bestow compassion on bound souls, one should join them [in ritual] for the [sake of the] soul (\skt{ātmani}).</TR>
<NOTE>The sense of the emphatically placed particle \skt{api} we assume to be meant to convey that the wherewithal for \skt{nitya} rites was already gathered, and now the ritualist has “also” gathered the above-mentioned items required for the \skt{naimittika} rite of \skt{dīkṣā}.  This is thus arguably a further indication that the \skt{nitya} rites, and thus also the wherewithal (\skt{nityāṅgāni}) were described in an earlier section of the text, namely the \ttl{Nityakriyānusandhāna}.
The second half of the above verse could instead be understood to mean: “[next], by means of the power of the Lord to bestow compassion on bound souls, he should join [śivatva] in the soul.”
</NOTE>
<TEXT>tatra śodhyādhvanaḥ pūrvvaṃ sādhāraṃ sakalaṃ śivam |</TEXT>
<APP> \va <LEM>śodhyādhvanaḥ</LEM> \emend; sodhyādhanaḥ \msA </APP>
<APP> \vb <LEM>śivam</LEM> \emend; śivaṃm \msA </APP>
<TEXT>nyasya nyaset tam{ }adhvānaṃ nayayuktyā saśaktikam || 2:36||</TEXT>
<APP> \vd <LEM>nayayuktyā</LEM> In the top margin above this, the scribe has added the gloss: sṛṣṭikrameṇa </APP>
<APP> \vd <LEM>saśaktikam</LEM> \emend; sasaktikaṃ \msA </APP>
<TR>Before [installing] the path that is to be purified, having [first] installed (\skt{nyasya}) Sakala Śiva, along with Ādhāraśakti (\skt{sādhāraṃ}), there  [viz.\ on the equipment that has been gathered together for the initiation]
he should [then] install that path, along with Śakti (\skt{saśaktikam}), in accordance with logic.
 </TR>
<NOTE> In the top margin, above \skt{nayayuktyā}, which we have translated with “in accordance with logic”, the scribe has added \skt{sṛṣṭikrameṇa}, which we take to be a gloss on \skt{nayayuktyā} that explains that, in this context, logic requires that the path is installed in the order of creation of its constituents, and not in the reverse order of resorption (\skt{saṃhārakrameṇa}).
Here we have supposed that \skt{tatra} must refer to the physical locus onto which the \skt{nyāsa} is to be performed. The only candidate for a referent of the \skt{tatra} seems to be the \skt{naimittikāṅgāni}, the equipment for the performance of an initiation which has been listed at length above.
The expression \skt{śodhyādhvanaḥ pūrvvaṃ} could alternatively be understood to mean “before [performing] the purification of the path”. In other words, \skt{śodhyādhvan} would be equivalent in sense to \skt{adhvaśodhana}.
</NOTE>
