<TR1>Optionally one may to place suitable niṣkala [Śiva] in [the acts of] restraining or in conferring benefits; later in the act of controlling (vaśyasya) one has to place/invoke pervading sakalaśiva, who has the power [of controlling].</TR1>
<TR2>Optionally (vā) one should then (atha) afterwards (paścāt) install (nyaset) [also] Niṣkala Śiva, who is capable of occluding (nigrahe) and liberating (anugrahe) that (tasya) soul who is to be controlled (vaśyasya), who maintains control (vaśinam), [and] who pervades that [Sakala Śiva].</TR2>
<TR3> One should then (atha) afterwards (paścāt) install (nyaset) [also] Niṣkala Śiva, who is capable of occluding (nigrahe) or else (vātha) of liberating (anugrahe) the (tasya) soul who is to be controlled (vaśyasya), who maintains control (vaśinam), [and] who pervades that [Sakala Śiva].</TR3>
<NOTE>It is not certain whether any of these interpretations is correct.  In one, we have taken \skt{vā} to mean “optionally”, but it could also be interpreted to mean “Alternatively…”. And perhaps the two halves of this verse are meant to present two different options instead of one. It is possible that the \skt{nyāsa} of either Sakala and Niṣkala is based on the status of the initiand, who may be \skt{bubhukṣu} or \skt{mumukṣu}. But 2:2 above seem to suggest that this chapter is primarily about \skt{bhūtidīkṣā}, in other words about the \skt{bubhukṣu}.</NOTE>
