<TEXT>atha prabodhanistṛṃśapāṇī rakṣodiśi sthitaḥ |</TEXT>
<TEXT>pūrvvottarānanaṃ kuryāc{ }chaivaṃ dhāma viśeṣataḥ || 2:40||</TEXT>
<TR>Then, holding the “sword of knowledge” in his hand (\skt{prabodhanistṛṃśapāṇiḥ}), he should stand in the South West [corner of the sacrificial space], and cause the Śaiva glory/residence to face North East particularly.</TR>
<NOTE>This ritual object made of thirty-six blades of darbha-grass is usually called a \skt{jñānakhaḍga} or \skt{jñānāsi} (see TAK2 s.v.).  What is the \skt{śaivaṃ dhāma} that he causes to face towards the North East ?  Usually, if the ritual officiant stands in one corner, he will be facing towards the other.  So we would expect, since he stands in the SW, that he should himself be facing towards the NE.  So perhaps, in view of the preceding verse, in which he has identified himself as the principal substrate of Śiva, \skt{śaivaṃ dhāma} may refer to the officiant himself.  Cf.\ SP3, 1:29ab (\skt{jñānakhaḍgakaraḥ sthitvā nairṛtyām udagānanaḥ}), which may express almost the same idea.  For Somaśambhu, though positioned in the SW, the officiant faces N, and not NE.  But it is conceivable that the expression \skt{pūrvottarānanaṃ} means “facing East or North”. </NOTE>
