<NOTE>We understand \skt{kalākalāpam udbodhya} to refer to the rite referred to elsewhere as \skt{kalāprakalpana} (see TAK2, s.v.), which consists in laying out the five \skt{kalā}s in and around the \skt{kuṇḍa} in the positions entailed by their homologisation with the five faces of Sadāśiva.  We do not have Brahmaśambhu's earlier description of the \skt{kuṇḍasaṃskāra}s, which may have been mentioned in his \ttl{Niyānusandhāna}, and so we don't know whether they were totally twelve in number, or whether there were more.</NOTE>
