<TEXT>avaguṇṭhanam{ }atroktaṃ svasāmarthyapradarśanāt || 90||</TEXT> 2:89||
<TR>The relationship between parts and possessor of parts is a grouping of property-possessor and properties that are not adventitious.  Here the act of enveloping [performed by the aṅgas of Śiva] is enjoined because it proclaims His power.</TR>
<NOTE>Assuming that the above interpretation of the first half of this verse is correct, what we assume it to mean is this: an ańga (part) is connected to its possessor (aṅgin) by an inseparable connection.  In other words, Śiva's aṅgas are inseparable from Himself. So when something is ritually enveloped in his aṅgas, it proclaims to potential obstructors that the power of Śiva is inhabiting and protecting it from them.</NOTE>
